"Yes, Captain. They should be on their way by now, they were still in the canteen, picking up their rations."
"We will be relocated to the advanced forward base I-131, fifty miles outside Ianlos. Our mission is to support the ongoing siege and the later attack on Ianlos to drive out the Rebels. There, we will establish a base at the foot of the mountains," Shaw explained. "Departure to your units and mount up."
The company dissolved into its respective squads, and the soldiers were distributed among the tanks by the sergeants. Cohren boarded one of the tanks further up front in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but knew little about them. He sat sideways and let his legs dangle, while adjusting his backpack and the radio equipment, which was connected to his headphones and laryngophone microphone.
"Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?", Nemic asked after they had settled in.
"Do you mean the rooster he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning when they had taken the animal with them on a farm. "Yes, I think so."
Crewman looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his team. From the corner of his eye he could make out the movement of a small rooster, that was scanning its surroundings by constantly turning its head.
"Yes, he is still with him," Cohren replied, as the hatch of the tank opened and the commander came into view.
"All tanks are advancing," said the commander slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the tank and Stryker unit roared as they moved into action. The Kronos tank, which Cohren was riding, jolted as the brakes were released and they fell into formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania Plain. Despite the winter storms having frozen the swamp areas and covered the forests in snow, the mud was omnipresent.
About an hour later, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. "Lieutenant, have you been here since the start of the war?"
"Yes, Operation Firestorm", Cohren replied. "We thought it would be wrapped up in a few weeks, but we underestimated it."
"Underestimated is strongly understated," Nemic interjected into the conversation. "Their arsenal and mass of soldiers caught us off guard. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and the Erebus only last month. We should have even seen them on our way."
"I stand firmly on the side of the Federation," Orson said defiantly. "I won't be scared by these terrorists."
"That's what you're saying now. But I've seen that most eighteen-year-old recruits like you quickly take cover as soon as they hear a shot", Craith explained.
"We'll see about that," Cohren said laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
"Cohren's radio crackled with 'Exodus XO, Exodus CO.' 'We're receiving heat signatures, about 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right.'"
He climbed up on the tank and put on his special glasses. As he switched them to "thermal imaging", he could recognize the signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see her", Cohren replied over his laryngemicrophone.
"Are they hostile?", asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"I don't see them," Cohren replied. He reached for his microphone and said: "Exodus Company, open fire only when under fire. Let's lure them out."
As they drew near, the point-like heat signatures took shape. As they approached even closer, one of them hastily ran off to fetch something. It immediately returned to the small knoll where the others were. The figures lay down on the ground; they took up firing positions.
"We have enemy contact," Shaw yelled over the radio, as orange-tracer rounds were fired from the ridge. As the tanks came under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket whizzed by and slammed into the ground behind the formation, exploding and scattering debris and rubble on one of the tanks. Another struck the side of a Stryker, an APS Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammo flew into the air.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 meters. Fire at will", the commander of the tank column screamed over radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flew towards the hill and exploded, throwing mud and rock into the air.
"Send in the Sentis," Knoxx called, who was observing the hill with binoculars. The rear door of a Cerberus opened and an unarmed soldier came out, wearing a special headset. He barked orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially known as Sentinels, stormed out. With their thin, metallic arms and legs swinging forward, they sprinted off. They wore their weapons on their backs.
"Kill or capture?", Craith asked, watching.
"It looked like they'd been captured," Cohren conjectured, as the two Sentinels disappeared into the ash and smoke cloud. Screams and shots echoed off the ridge, but quickly died down. Shortly afterwards, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots left tracks in the ground. After they had returned to the safety of the train, they threw the figure to the ground. It groaned in pain as it landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw went to the figure, which was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," replied the sentinel. "The rest fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who stood nearby. "Get rid of that guy for me!"
